\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 5 - beguines lived in a medieval world governed by men and according to values that validated masculine experience. The mere search for a self by a oman was perceived as undermining \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93male privelege,\u8221\'94 even though that was probably not her intent.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 After gregorian reform - 1073-1085 - laymen began to take their faith into their own hands, discontent a phenomenon called vita apostolica. Beguines were a powerful expression of vita apostolica. First followers as described in Acts were the ideal believers. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Followers of the way\u8221\'94 - atmosphere of anticiation, awe, and unaffected joy amongst believers. Essential to Followers of the Way was to live by the Christian baptismal creed, \u8220\'93There is no such thing as Jew and Greek, slave and free, male and female, for you are all one person in Christ Jesus.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pg18 - imitating early christian lifestyle as literally as possible  - lives of profound simplicity, generosity to the poor, taking caer of lepers, and daily attendance at prayer in a church. Beguines and other laypeopleasked themselves: How did Jesus want us to live? How did early followers of Jesus behave? Why does our own church not look like the church of the early apostles - why is corruption tolerated? }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Vita apostolica - voluntary poverty . Restore the church to its original primitive exression. Reacting iwth growing alarm and disdain to the new market economy based on coinange and money-lending with interest charged.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mendicant orders - domincan and franciscan - both began in the earl ythirteenth century. Mendicants took religious vows and freely moved around europe to preach and teach in universities churches, and public squares; they did not have the same attachment to a specific monastary as the monks and nuns. In princpile, lived off alms and thus were referred to as wandering beggars.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Beguines lived in the comfort with the new market economy - in fact, their freedom depended on it. Some vocal leaders of the vita apostolica demanded that followers seek absolute privation even if this privation limited the ability to aid those unable to care for themselves. But beguines disagreed, and they used their keen business sense to earn the money needed to help the poor. Beguines ooled their resources in order to serve the sick and destitute by building and operating infirmaries and almshouses.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 In the early thirteenth century, the sisters Countess Joan (1194-1244) and Countes Margaret of Flanders and Hainault invested a significant portion of their weath to establish secular coeducational schools (for children) in their realm to teach reading, writing and simple mathematics. Joan believed that educated adults were a boon to the economy as they could make more money, thus spend more money , and so grow tax revenues. Beguines benefited from this increased literacy, both in their own education and in establishing schools as a chosen ministry. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Literacy begain to rise, - major intellectual shift 1100s, universiteis began to separate from the great monastery and cathedral schools; universiteis at bologna, paris, and oxford. Women not permitted - beguines invited academic teachers to their homes. Some turned into supporters of beg, some enemies.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Many women became beguines as a result of literacy - searching for biblical and other spiritual texts in the vernacular, beguines met to study and debate them eaning of these texts.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 An increasingly educated laity demanded effective preaching from religious leaders. Followers of the vita apostolcia had grown intolerant of lax and mediocre preaching, especially from clerics whose private lives were a disaster. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Beguines like Dante - Mechthild of Magdeburg.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 With the rise of the troubadours in the late eleventh century developed a lifestyle and art form called fine amour, or amour courtoise, courly love. It spread from souther n france across europe and enjoyed great popularity for two hundred years or mor. Troubadors wrote, collected, and performed lyrics that glorified love and raised it to spiritual and metaphorical heights of honor, much in the tradition of the biblical song of songs. Beguines expanded this notion of hte \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93the heart\u8217\'92s yearning for hte beloved\u8221\'94 to express the human search for God, and the beguine hadewijch is considered the master par excellance in expressing her mysticl visions and teachings with the language of courtly love.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Francis of assisi and clare of assissi, }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
