\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Pg. 22}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Marie d\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92oignies, and Jacques de Vitry}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Married at fourteen to John, wealthy sone of another nivelles family. Once married and away from her parents scrutiny ,marie began a more adruous ascetical observance of fasting, prayer, and almsgiving. After a few months of marriage, ohn experienced a conversion in which he came to desire a deepre relationship with god. Marie and john enjoed one another\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s company, and they framed their married life around a daily routine of prayer, fasts, aphysical labor, and works of charity. Soon the two decided as was common in via apostolica, to live together as brother and sister, eschewing sexual relations. Instead they focused their passion and energies on serving God. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Abandoned their home in nivelles and moved to nearby williambroux, where an informal community following the vita apostolica lived alongside lepers. John\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s brother, master guido, served as chaplain of local church\u8230\'85Marie\u8217\'92s dedication to serving hte poor and to prayer gained renown, and she was becoming known as a \u8220\'93living saint\u8221\'94. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Marie earned a reputation for the efficacious power of her prayer. She was regarded as having the ability to read souls, which meant that she could gaze upon a person and effectively indetify the status of their salvation: was the seeker in a stat of sin, or guilty of unconfessed sins? Marie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s intent was to heal a person spiritually by calling them to repentance.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 People constantly sought her out, interrupting her ministry with the lepers. She yearned for a more intense life of prayer and solitutde and thus moved to a cell near the priory of st. Nicholas in oignies. She deepend her life of fasting and prayer while living there as a recluse, but also met with individuals for spiritual counseling and sent words of exhortation to those whose lives needed correction.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Around 1208, theologian jacques de vitry arrived form paris in order to meet marie, and eventually became her disciple. At marie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s encouragement, he briefly returend to paris to be ordained, and then continued his life and ministry at oigines, serving lepers and the destitute. He referred to marie as his magistra.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Died in 1213, her fame spread wide and inspired women to follow her example. Jacques de vitry composed his life of marie d\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92oigines after her death as a nargument in support of the beguines whom he had observed in his travles. He regard beguines as exemplars of the apostolic life and as a bulwark against heresies.  After preaching the albigensian crusade, as well as the fifth crusade, vitry was chosen as bishop of acre in the holy land. He served there from 1216 onward for a number of years while staying depely involved in european church and political affairs. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Vitry\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s recounting pg.27 changing events to make the story better. \u8220\'93Biographical device\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Ida of Nivelles - ran away from home at 9, taking with her a psalter.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Juetta of Huy. Eighteen when husband died, left to raise two children on her own. Five years later, she left her home and children in order to serve lepers at a nold chapel across the river meuse. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Douceline of digne 1215-1274 - beguine mystic, douceline experienced repeated ecstatic moments in prayer - coudeline prized the lowly humble place in society. When her followers expressed concern that douceline was treated with contempt by her dteractors, she responded: truly it is my honor and my glory, my jy and my crown that the world holds us in great scorn, and that everyone disdains us.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
