\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 In their embodied prayer, many beguines sooned on the cross with jesus christ himself, not as passive observers but sharing in the terror of the crucifixion; . }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Angela of foligno believed that a loving relationship ith god in prayer was not the exclusive domain of the}{\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cf1  profesisonally religious}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  but available for all\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  and then went on to describe in her Instructions what this inner journey might be like.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Angela\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s relationship with god was \u8220\'93a spiral rather than a linear one, for in their respective journeys God and ANgela come together and apart, they approach and abandon each other, so that this journey though made of steps, is not, or can be, a straight path.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Three forms of prayer - physical prayer is the expression of the heart\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s aspirations through words and bodily modtion (kneeling down). Mental prayer is when our mind is in deep meditation and solely pondering the divine presence, wihtout any distraction. And supernatural prayer is when God - who gives this gift and infuses it with divine presence - lifts the soul up so it is stretched beyond its normal limites. Then the soul understands more about god than would otherwise be possible. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Hen we know who we are and who god is, we love. And when we love, we want to possess what we love. That is the sign of true love. The lover is changed - not in part but wholly - into the beloved.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Beguines aspired to enter into an intense experinece of the passion adn death of christ in order to feel what he might have felt. Some of them embraced illness and harsh ascetical practices, believing that they might imitate jesus\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s suffering on earth in an effort to plumb the depths of chhrist\u8217\'92s humanity at the moment of his most insistent and terrifying humanness - the moment of his dying.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Hadewijch letter - WE all want to be god along with god; but god knos that there are fe of us who want to be man with him in his humanity, to carry his cross with him, to hang upon it with him, to pay with him the debt of human kind. If we look at ourselves we can see that this is true; we iwll not suffer anything, we will not endure. Just let our hearts be stabbed by the slightest grief, just let someone say a scornful or slanderous word about us, let anyone act against our reputation or our peace or our will, adn at once we are mortally injured: we know exactly what we want and what we do not want, there are som any different things which give us pleasure or pain, now we want this and now we want tha, our joy today is our sorrow toomorrow, we ould like to be here, we would like to be there, we do not want something and then we want it, and in everything all we are thinking of is our own satisfaction and how we can best seek it.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Agnes Blannbekin - rapture = the soul brings three things with her after such rapture: first ,a certain noble indignation and contempt against all that is orldly and disgust against all that exists, except for god. And such contempt functions like a wall against sin. Secondly, there is a certain hidden sweetness. Thirdly, there is burning desire and languishing love for god. The first enables the soul. The second pours the soul into god, so that she will be received all the more deeply into god the more that she tastes of such lusciousness. The third iluminates the soul and makes her shine with light.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The intimate experience of contemplative gazing on the eucharist was a constant theme in beguine writings. Their passion was to see and gaze upon the host - not to partake. For beguines, abstaining out of awe was equal to receiving in confidence and joy.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Agnes had taken communion, she was suddenly filled with such sweetness of spirit htat it spilled into her flesh insuch a way that there was not one place on her whole body where she could not feel physically the invaluable sweetness. And she remained in this sweetness physically as much as spiritually for the whole day, flowing over with delights and spiritual joy.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 How could an imperfect person be allowed into God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s presence? Enter purgatory - to extinguish lingering sin and prepare them to dwell in God\u8217\'92s place.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Prayers a precious ointment to the damned.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Albigensian heretics\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Church leaders and layiety alike knew without doubt that beguines had the power to release people from purgatory through intercessory prayer.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Purgatory was god\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s prison. Closely related to penance.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Beguines believed that purgatory depened one\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s capacity to experience and dwell with god; they taught purgatory was about love- god allowed purgatory to exist so that ultimately humans could spend eternity with god. ..on one hand, god was right to demand justice because humanity, in its sinning, had disobeyed god. On the other hand, the god who is love could not possibly want anyone to remain in hell.at times beguines felt scandalous in \u8216\'91defying\u8217\'92 god\u8217\'92s right to demand jusice from a sinner because they would accept onto themselves on behalf of the sinner the punishment owed. Yet beguines explained that love impelled them to asume this burden, believing that God\u8217\'92s love, rather than hell, would ultimately prevail.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 God is love\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85. Hadewijch, no one need to fear hell because even the path into hell ultimately leads to God. Beguine wrtings reveal some women \u8220\'93negotiating hell away from God\u8221\'94 because they could not imagine God who is Love tolerating souls suffering in hell. Diisstancing themselves from the groing comfort of medieval men and women with indulgences, beguines taught that people should not serve others out of hope of earning entry into heaven that way, because god\u8217\'92s love could not be bought with money or earned with good deeds.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Christina the Astonishing - near death experience in 1182. Her biographer wrote that christian died and visited hell, purgatory, and heaven, then came back to life with great zeal to free souls from purgatory.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cf1 Love as boundary attraction or boundary negation. Hate as boundary attraction. Love as desire to destroy a boundary, Hate as a desire to build one.}
